Hey there! Passing a variable by reference in C# can be done by using the `ref` keyword. However, if you only have a `MemberInfo` object for the variable, you would need to first get the actual variable using reflection and then pass it by reference.

Here is an example code snippet demonstrating how you can achieve this:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Reflection;

public class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        int myVariable = 10;
        MemberInfo myMemberInfo = typeof(Program).GetField("myVariable");

        if (myMemberInfo is FieldInfo)
        {
            FieldInfo myFieldInfo = (FieldInfo)myMemberInfo;
            object obj = Activator.CreateInstance(typeof(Program));
            int value = (int)myFieldInfo.GetValue(obj);

            Console.WriteLine("Original value: " + value);

            // Passing the variable by reference
            ref int refVariable = ref value;
            refVariable++;

            Console.WriteLine("Updated value: " + value);
        }
    }
}
```

In this code snippet, we first retrieve the `FieldInfo` object corresponding to the variable using reflection. Then, we create an instance of the class containing the variable and get the current value of the variable using `GetValue` method. 
After that, we assign the value to a new variable `refVariable` by reference and make changes to it. 

