Sure thing! I'd be happy to help you with that. Let's create a fixed size concurrent queue in C# from scratch that supports enqueuing and dequeuing awaitable tasks.

Here's the implementation:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class FixedSizeConcurrentQueue
{
    private Queue<Task> queue = new Queue<Task>();
    private int maxSize;

    public FixedSizeConcurrentQueue(int maxSize)
    {
        this.maxSize = maxSize;
    }

    public async Task Enqueue(Task task)
    {
        while (queue.Count >= maxSize)
        {
            await Task.Delay(100); // You can change the delay as per your requirements
        }

        lock (queue)
        {
            queue.Enqueue(task);
        }

        await task;

        DequeueCompletedTasks();
    }

    private void DequeueCompletedTasks()
    {
        lock (queue)
        {
            while (queue.Count > 0 && queue.Peek().IsCompleted)
            {
                queue.Dequeue();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task<Task> Dequeue()
    {
        Task taskToDequeue;

        do
        {
            DequeueCompletedTasks();

            lock (queue)
            {
                taskToDequeue = queue.Count > 0 ? queue.Peek() : null;
            }

            if (taskToDequeue == null)
            {
                await Task.Delay(100); // You can change the delay as per your requirements
            }
        } while (taskToDequeue == null);

        return taskToDequeue;
    }
}
```

This code defines a `FixedSizeConcurrentQueue` class that can enqueue and dequeue awaitable tasks. The queue has a fixed size specified during initialization. The `Enqueue` method allows tasks to be added to the queue, and the `Dequeue` method returns the task that is at the head of the queue and has completed running.

