Certainly! Here is a MATLAB code that can identify the tense used in a given sentence:

```matlab
function identify_tense(sentence)
    % Define a list of keywords for each tense
    present_tense = {'am', 'is', 'are', 'have', 'has', 'do', 'does'};
    past_tense = {'was', 'were', 'had', 'did'};
    future_tense = {'will', 'shall', 'going to'};

    % Tokenize the sentence into individual words
    words = strsplit(sentence, ' ');

    % Check for the presence of tense keywords in the sentence
    present_count = sum(ismember(words, present_tense));
    past_count = sum(ismember(words, past_tense));
    future_count = sum(ismember(words, future_tense));

    % Determine the tense based on the count of tense keywords
    if present_count > 0
        disp('Present Tense');
    elseif past_count > 0
        disp('Past Tense');
    elseif future_count > 0
        disp('Future Tense');
    else
        disp('Tense not identified');
    end
end
```

You can use this function by calling `identify_tense('Your sentence here')`. It will then identify whether the given sentence is in the Present Tense, Past Tense, Future Tense, or it could not be identified. I hope this code helps you with your task! Let me know if you need any further assistance.

